data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class plus better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere gives unhelpful failure messages like "Expected: True, Actual: False."

Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    var admin = users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)`** â€” on failure reports *"Expected: 3, Actual: 5"* instead of just *"False"*
- **`Assert.IsNotNull(admin)`** â€” clearer intent than `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)`
- **`CollectionAssert`** â€” provides `AllItemsAreNotNull`, `AllItemsAreUnique`, `Contains`, `AreEqual` (order-sensitive), `AreEquivalent` (order-insensitive), etc.
- **Message parameters** â€” add context to `Assert.IsTrue` when LINQ predicates are unavoidable

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**

```csharp
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expectedList, actualList);  // same items, any order
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expectedList, actualList);       // same items, same order
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(users);
CollectionAssert.IsSubsetOf(subset, superset);
```

> **Tip:** If you want even richer fluent assertions, consider adding [FluentAssertions](https://fluentassertions.com) â€” it gives you `users.Should().HaveCount(3).And.OnlyContain(u => u.IsActive)`.
